<h2>In-class Lab 2.2</h2>
<ol type="I">
<li class="row0">
<p>Exercise 1</p>
<ol type="1">
<li class="row1">
<p>
If using your Linux VM, create directory <b>lab02</b> under your
<b>/var/www/labs</b> directory. Otherwise create directory <b>lab02</b> under
the document root of whatever web server you are using. On the MATC Windows lab
computers, using XAMPP on your external USB drive, the document root will be
something like: <b>E:\xampp\htdocs</b> Note that your external
drive may be using a different drive letter!
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>In <b>jEdit</b> or another text editor, create an HTML form file that contains 
two text fields.</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
The first text field will hold the name of the form user.
The second text field will hold the phone number of the form user.
</p></li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
The ACTION attribute of the form tag should be assigned the name of the PHP script
that will handle your form. Call it <b>lab2x2script.php</b>
</p></li>
<li class="row1">
<p>Save the form file as <b>lab2x2form.html</b> in the <b>lab02</b> directory you created in
step #1.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>Open <b>lab2x2form.html</b> in a browser to test whether it contains syntax
errors, and fix any errors you encounter.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>Exercise 2</p>
</li>
<ol>
<li class="row1">
<p>Create a PHP script named <b>lab2x2script.php</b> and save it into your lab02
directory.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1"><p>
Use the <b>extract($_REQUEST)</b> funtion call to create PHP variables with the
same names as the HTML form fields.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>Alternatively, you can create PHP variables to hold the values of the fields from
the HTML form yourself.</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>For example, if there is a form field called "name", since HTML forms use the
GET method by default, your variable assignment statement would look like:</p>
<blockquote><code>
$name = $_GET['name'];<br>
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>Add PHP code blocks embedded in HTML to print the descriptions and values
of the two fields entered in the lab2x2form.html HTML form.</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
If you have time, and are already somewhat familiar with the <b>if..else</b>
construct, create code to test whether either of the form fields is empty, and
display a "no value submitted" message instead of the field value if that is the
case. <b>Note that this step is <i>not</i> required!</b>
</p>

</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>Test your code and show it to your instructor.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</ol>
